<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO ART</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jul 22  5:54:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art,<br><br>
Thanks for your post. <br><br>
My position, and the reason that I came out with the things that I have said, is to show that one didn't have to be a &quot;communist sympathizer&quot; to be against what was happening in Vietnam.<br><br>
I have said repeatedly that my experience in Vietnam opened my eyes to lots of things AND that we don't have to call people names in order build a better perception of ourselves.<br><br>
The way to get across the point that GI's in Vietnam were capable of good is to WRITE about the good. Then let students and other people make up their own minds. People who believe in their works don't need to convince themselves of the merit of these works by blasting at the other side. When we say we are searching for the TRUTH do we understand the implications?<br><br>
What am I getting at? If we are ever going to come together as people we need to realize that there is room for everyone at the table. If one side is excluded by intimidating words, then it is necessary for others to throw a wrench into the works. It is not a fun job. Things grind to a halt, but the faithful make the necessary repairs and start rolling again.<br><br>
Yes, it is necessary to vent our anger once we have broken our &quot;silence&quot;. Yet, a much higher calling is to try to pick our way down the path that leads to the other person's camp - hoping that he is doing the same, so that somewhere in the middle there will be a meeting - maybe even a handshake.<br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


